This paper is likely to belong to the computer graphics (cs.GR) sub-category as it deals with rendering isosurfaces in volumetric fields. It also involves deep learning networks, which suggests it could also belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of convolutional neural networks for learning suggests it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of motion loss, which suggests it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the use of deep learning for scan completion and image super-resolution suggests it could also belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category.
